@flexiarg vsatlatarium/anthology-as-filter
@title Anthology as Constellation Filter
@audience curators, facilitators, digital library architects
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [📚/选]
@references [vsatlas/minimal-linking-pilot vsatlas/facilitation-scaffolds vsatlas/interpretive-views]

! conclusion:
  Use pilot-defined story subsets as anthology filters that reshape the
  constellation to a focused sub-world, preserving all spatial and
  relational affordances.

  + context: You are curating viewing experiences for different audiences or sessions from the same corpus. This does not apply when all stories are always relevant to all viewers.
  + IF:
    A facilitator, exhibition, or course module needs a focused subset of
    the full story world.

  + HOWEVER:
    Showing everything overwhelms; building separate installations
    duplicates effort.

  + THEN:
    Reuse the pilot (anthology) model to filter stories at query time
    (?pilot=N). The dome re-projects around fewer clusters, vertical
    spread is clamped for small collections, and all navigation
    (planetarium, geomview, VR) works on the filtered set.

  + BECAUSE:
    Filtering is cheaper than forking. The same relational infrastructure
    serves multiple curatorial frames without duplicating data or code.

  + STATUS:
    status[ready]
    evidence[VSATLATARIUM ?pilot= filtering — pilot chips, view-toggle preservation]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Test whether small anthologies (2–4 stories) feel spatially coherent or sparse.]
    next[Explore nested anthologies (pilot within pilot) for multi-session programmes.]
    next[Add anthology selection to the VR interface (controller menu or gaze-based selector).]
